The article discusses the Supreme Court's decision to uphold the Affordable Care Act, also known as Obamacare. It highlights the benefits and protections provided by the law, such as preventing insurance companies from canceling policies or denying coverage based on pre-existing conditions. The article also mentions the coverage of preventive care, rebates for excessive administrative costs, and savings on prescription drugs for seniors. It emphasizes that the law will offer quality, affordable health insurance plans for the 30 million uninsured Americans starting in 2014. The article also mentions tax credits for middle-class families and small businesses to make insurance more affordable. It discusses the support for state implementation of Affordable Insurance Exchanges, which are marketplaces for individuals and small businesses to compare and choose health plans. The article concludes by calling for bipartisan cooperation to provide security for the middle class and focus on the economy and job creation.